The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Sunday, July 18, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 ITC Hotels has posted a first-quarter net profit of Rs 6.92 crore as compared with Rs 0.59 crore in the corresponding previous quarter. Total income has increased 37 per cent to Rs 42.63 crore in the reporting quarter from Rs 31.12 crore in 2003-04. The company has also announced a dividend of 20 per cent or Rs 2 per share for 2003-04. 																								 Zensar Technologies Ltd, a Pune-based IT and BPO major, has posted a 73.89 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 5.53 crore on a consolidated basis in the first quarter ended June 30 against Rs 3.18 crore in the year-ago period. The companys total revenue rose to Rs 77.46 crore in April-June compared with Rs 58.62 crore in the same period a year ago.																								 Vanavil Dyes amp; Chemicals Ltd, a subsidiary of Colour-Chem Ltd, has posted a quantum leap in net profit at Rs 35.94 lakh in its first quarter ended June 30 compared with Rs 7.97 in the previous year period. However, the companys income from operations fell marginally to Rs 11.25 crore from Rs 11.73 crore posted during the same period a year ago, Vanavil Dyes amp; Chemicals said.																								 Jindal Stainless Ltd has reported 7 per cent year-on-year growth in net profit in the first quarter of 2004-05 at Rs 50.1 crore. The net sales of the company in April-June increased 9 per cent compared with the year-ago period to touch Rs 643.2 crore.																								 Goodlass Nerolac Paints Ltd has posted a 73.40 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 15.52 crore in the first quarter of the fiscal ended June 30 against Rs 8.95 crore in the same period of the previous fiscal. The companys board has approved a 125 per cent dividend for the previous fiscal, Goodlass Nerolac said in a release.																								 Coromandel Fertilisers Ltd, a part of the $1.2 billion Murugappa group, has reported a net profit of Rs 21.01 crore in the first quarter of this fiscal compared with a net loss of Rs 31 lakh in April-June 2003. The net profit included Rs 11.29 crore the company received towards interest on income tax refund, a company statement said.																								 Kochi Refineries Ltd, a subsidiary of Bharat Petroleum Corporation, has recorded a profit of Rs 555 crore in 2003-04, a growth of 21 per cent over Rs 456 crore recorded in the previous year. The company has announced a dividend of 120 per cent (Rs 12 per share) for 2003-04. The outflow on this account would be to the tune of Rs 187 crore, he said.																								 Mphasis BFL has reported an 81 per cent jump in net profit at Rs 35.38 crore for the first quarter ended June 30, aided by foreign exchange gains and deferred income tax credit. The Bangalore-based firm had posted a net profit of Rs 19.49 crore in the corresponding period last fiscal, a company statement said here. ADVERTISEMENT
